\strong{Part One}

You need to cross a vast \emph{firewall}. The firewall consists of several
layers, each with a \emph{security scanner} that moves back and forth across
the layer. To succeed, you must not be detected by a scanner.

By studying the firewall briefly, you are able to record (in your puzzle
input) the \emph{depth} of each layer and the \emph{range} of the scanning area
for the scanner within it, written as \code{depth: range}. Each layer has a
thickness of exactly \code{1}. A layer at depth \code{0} begins immediately inside
the firewall; a layer at depth \code{1} would start immediately after that.

For example, suppose you've recorded the following:\preformatted{0: 3
1: 2
4: 4
6: 4
}

This means that there is a layer immediately inside the firewall (with
range \code{3}), a second layer immediately after that (with range \code{2}), a
third layer which begins at depth \code{4} (with range \code{4}), and a fourth
layer which begins at depth 6 (also with range \code{4}). Visually, it might
look like this:\preformatted{ 0   1   2   3   4   5   6
[ ] [ ] ... ... [ ] ... [ ]
[ ] [ ]         [ ]     [ ]
[ ]             [ ]     [ ]
                [ ]     [ ]
}

Within each layer, a security scanner moves back and forth within its
range. Each security scanner starts at the top and moves down until it
reaches the bottom, then moves up until it reaches the top, and repeats.
A security scanner takes \emph{one picosecond} to move one step. Drawing
scanners as \code{S}, the first few picoseconds look like this:\preformatted{Picosecond 0:
