In this situation, you are \emph{caught} in layers \code{0} and \code{6}, because your
packet entered the layer when its scanner was at the top when you
entered it. You are \emph{not} caught in layer \code{1}, since the scanner moved
into the top of the layer once you were already there.

The \emph{severity} of getting caught on a layer is equal to its \emph{depth}
multiplied by its \emph{range}. (Ignore layers in which you do not get
caught.) The severity of the whole trip is the sum of these values. In
the example above, the trip severity is \code{0*3 + 6*4 = 24}.

